            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XIX-XX.R4</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Affery&rsquo;s dreams [...]</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-2dc3ddb2-7fff-7e16-70bf-80f5b222233a\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The &ldquo;Mems for working the story round&rdquo; established the device of connecting the revelations in this chapter to Affery&rsquo;s dreams (see LD.Mems1). However, since Arthur cannot be present to ask Affery to fulfill her earlier promise, Dickens &ldquo;has to&rdquo; make Pancks into Arthur&rsquo;s &ldquo;deputy&rdquo;: &ldquo;&lsquo;[H]e is ill and in prison&ndash;ill and in prison, poor fellow&ndash;if he was here,&rsquo; said Mr. Pancks, taking one step aside towards the window-seat, and laying his right hand upon the stocking; &lsquo;he would say, &ldquo;Affery, tell your dreams&rdquo;&rsquo;&rdquo; (LD 744-45). Dickens shortens this passage in proof, removing a section about Pancks&rsquo;s &ldquo;emphatic&rdquo; manner and his &ldquo;intimation of having something curious in reserve.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>"
        }
